## Issues with this Infrastructure

### 1. SSL Termination at the Load Balancer
SSL is terminated at the load balancer, meaning traffic between the load balancer and the backend servers (Server 1, Server 2) travels **unencrypted** (plain HTTP). If the internal network is compromised, traffic can be intercepted. The fix is to use end-to-end encryption (SSL all the way to the application servers), though this adds complexity.

### 2. Single Primary MySQL Server for Writes
Only the Primary MySQL node accepts write queries. If the Primary goes down, no writes can be performed until a Replica is manually or automatically promoted to Primary. This is still a SPOF for write operations. A true high-availability solution requires automatic failover (e.g., MySQL Group Replication or Galera Cluster).

### 3. Servers Have All Components (No Separation of Concerns)
Each server runs Nginx, the application server, and a monitoring agent together. If one component consumes excessive resources (e.g., a memory leak in the app), it degrades all other components on the same server. Ideally, web servers, application servers, and databases should be on separate dedicated machines to isolate failure domains and allow independent scaling.
